\section{$N=(2,0)$ AdS$_3$ algebra and fixing the basis}
The action we are going to construct corresponds to the partial spontaneous breaking of $N=(2,0)$ AdS$_3$ supersymmetry. To start with, let us define
the $N=(2,0)$ AdS$_3$ super algebra in a standard way as (see e.g. \cite{Kuz1})
\begin{eqnarray}\label{ads3}
&&\left[ M_{ab}, M_{cd}\right] = \epsilon_{ac} M_{bd}+\epsilon_{bd} M_{ac}+\epsilon_{ad}M_{bc}+\epsilon_{bc}M_{ad}\equiv \left(M\right)_{ab,cd}, {\nonumber} \\
&& \left[ M_{ab}, P_{cd}\right] = \left(P\right)_{ab,cd}, \quad \left[ P_{ab}, P_{cd}\right] = -\frac{m^2}{16} \left(M\right)_{ab,cd}, {\nonumber} \\
&& \left[ M_{ab}, Q_{c}\right] = \epsilon_{ac} Q_{b}+\epsilon_{bc} Q_{a} \equiv \left(Q\right)_{ab,c},\;
\left[ M_{ab}, {\overline Q}{}_{c}\right] =  \left({\overline Q}{}\right)_{ab,c}, {\nonumber} \\
&&  \left[ P_{ab}, Q_{c}\right] ={\rm i} \frac{m}{4}  \left(Q\right)_{ab,c}, \;
\left[ P_{ab}, {\overline Q}{}_{c}\right] ={\rm i} \frac{m}{4}  \left({\overline Q}{}\right)_{ab,c}, \quad
 \left[J,Q_a\right]=Q_a, \quad \left[J,{\overline Q}{}_a\right]=-{\overline Q}{}_a , {\nonumber} \\
&& \left\{ Q_a, {\overline Q}{}_b \right\} = 2 P_{ab}+{\rm i} \frac{m}{2} M_{ab}+ {\rm i} m \epsilon_{ab} J.
\end{eqnarray}
Here, the generators $M_{ab}=M_{ba}, P_{ab}=P_{ba},\; a,b=1,2$ form the bosonic AdS$_3$ algebra while the fermionic generators $Q_a, {\overline Q}{}_a$ together with the
$U(1)$ generator $J$ extend it to the $N=(2,0)$ AdS$_3$ one.

Note, that in our basis these generators obey the following conjugation rules

text:
\begin{equation}
\left(M_{ab}\right)^\dagger = - M_{ab},\;\left(P_{ab}\right)^\dagger = P_{ab},\;\left(J\right)^\dagger =J, \quad
\left( Q_a\right)^\dagger = {\overline Q}{}_a.
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}\label{newbasis1}
Q=Q_1+{\rm i} Q_2,\; {\overline Q}{}={\overline Q}{}_1-{\rm i} {\overline Q}{}_2,\quad P=P_{11}+P_{22}+{\rm i} \frac{m}{4}\left( M_{11}+M_{22} \right)+m J,
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}\label{N2sP}
\left\{Q,{\overline Q}{}\right\}= 2P,\qquad \left\{Q,Q\right\}=\left\{{\overline Q}{},{\overline Q}{}\right\} =\left[ P,Q\right] =\left[P, {\overline Q}{}\right]=0.
\end{equation}

